To compute $\mathbb{P}(aX + bY > c)$ for independent $X \sim N(\mu_{X}, \sigma_{X}^{2})$, $Y \sim N(\mu_{Y}, \sigma_{Y}^{2})$: \begin{enumerate}\item Form $W = aX + bY \sim N\!\left(a\mu_{X}+b\mu_{Y},\
 a^{2}\sigma_{X}^{2} + b^{2}\sigma_{Y}^{2}\right)$.

\item Standardise: $\mathbb{P}(W>c) = \mathbb{P}\!\left(Z > \frac{c - (a\mu_{X}+b\mu_{Y})}{\sqrt{a^{2}\sigma_{X}^{2}+b^{2}\sigma_{Y}^{2}}}\right)$.\end{enumerate}

**Gaussian Linear Inequality Probabilities.** Let $X, Y \sim N(0,1)$. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\arabic{*})]\item $X \perp\!\!\!\perp Y$. Compute $\mathbb{P}(X + 3Y > 0)$.

\item $X \perp\!\!\!\perp Y$. Compute $\mathbb{P}(X > 0,\ X + 3Y > 0)$.

\item $X$ and $Y$ have correlation $0.5$. Compute $\mathbb{P}(X > 3Y \mid X > 0)$.\end{enumerate}

**Uniform Sampling in the $n$-Ball.** \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item How do you sample uniformly in the unit disk $\{(x,y): x^{2}+y^{2}\leq1\}$?

\item How do you sample uniformly in the unit $n$-ball $\{x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}: \|x\|\leq1\}$?

\item Explain why sampling each coordinate uniformly on $[-1,1]$ and rejecting points outside the ball fails badly for large $n$.\end{enumerate}
